### 11. End-to-end verification against the built output

Read: `coding-playbook/workflow/testing`, `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`

This step runs the full render + build pipeline and validates against
the spec's `outcomes.desired` — file existence, one-canonical-file
rule, shape adherence, URL shape, drift. The implementor executes
these as shell commands during the session; they are not automated
tests but are the acceptance gate for the plan. Do NOT start a dev
server — the user runs `npm run dev` on port 3001 themselves. This
verification uses `npm run build` and static inspection of `out/`.

- [x] 11a. Run `npm run build`. Confirm the console output shows
        `og:render` running first, `llms:render` running second,
        and both succeeding before `next build` begins. Any order
        swap means the `&&` chain in `prebuild` is wrong.
- [x] 11b. Inspect `out/llms.txt`:
          - Exists at `out/llms.txt` (Next copies from `public/`).
          - First line is `# AIDE — Autonomous Intent-Driven Engineering`.
          - Second non-blank line starts with `> ` and contains
            both `AIDE` and `@aidemd-mcp/server`.
          - Contains exactly four `## ` H2 headings in the order
            Methodology, Commands, Agents, Skills.
          - Every bullet line matches
            `- [<title>](https://aidemd.dev/docs/<section>/<slug>): <desc>`
            or the no-description variant — no `.md` extensions,
            no relative links, no bare slugs.
          - Total bullet count equals `DocRegistry.routes.length`
            at build time (33 today). Record the exact count in the
            build log so future drift is visible.
          - grep for `AIDEY`, ` AID `, `llms-full.txt`, `ai.txt` —
            zero matches.
- [x] 11c. Inspect the HTTP content-type story: `out/llms.txt` is
        a real `.txt` file on disk, so GitHub Pages (and any static
        host) serves it as `text/plain; charset=utf-8` by default.
        No redirect, no HTML wrapper, no dynamic route. Confirm
        `out/llms.txt` is NOT wrapped in `<html>` or `<body>` tags —
        static inspection is enough; no network request needed.
- [x] 11d. Cross-check drift-resistance: touch any docs markdown
        file (e.g. `.aide/docs/aide-spec.md`) by adding a throwaway
        blank line, re-run `npm run build`, confirm `out/llms.txt`
        regenerated and the file is identical except for whatever
        derived content changed (title/description if frontmatter
        changed, nothing otherwise). Revert the throwaway edit.

### 12. Align the intent spec with migration reality

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`

- [x] Append a one-line entry under the spec's References section
      (not the body, not the frontmatter) noting that the plan
      landed and `public/llms.txt` is now the canonical artifact.
      Do not edit the `.aide` intent body otherwise — the spec is
      already authoritative and the whole point of AIDE is that the
      spec does not drift with implementation details.

## Decisions

- **Build-time integration is a `prebuild` npm script chained after
  `og:render`, not a Next plugin, not `generateStaticParams`, not a
  runtime route.** The `prebuild` hook is the house pattern on this
  project — `src/service/socialShare` established it, `og.png` lives
  in `public/`, and Next's static export copies `public/` into `out/`
  verbatim. Following the same pattern for `llms.txt` is the
  cheapest, most obvious path and keeps both static assets subject
  to the same drift-resistance discipline: if `npm run build`
  succeeds, both artifacts are fresh. Chaining with `&&` (rather than
  two sequential commands or a Node-level orchestrator) keeps the
  diff to `package.json` minimal and preserves exit-code semantics:
  a failure in og:render aborts llms:render aborts next build.

- **Consume docsRegistry via its public API, never a second walk.**
  The spec's drift-resistance outcome and the root intent's
  filesystem-driven-docs contract both require a single source of
  truth for the 33-route list. `docsRegistry.buildRegistry` is that
  source; `llmsTxt` imports it and filters/groups its output. The
  horizontal-isolation rule from the playbook's folder-structure
  note (`services never import a neighboring service's internals`)
  is satisfied because the import is of a public export, not a
  reach into `docsRegistry/walkDocsRoot/` or any helper subfolder.

- **Descriptions come from a new frontmatter-only accessor on
  docsRegistry (`getDocMeta`), not from `renderDoc`.** The spec's
  Strategy decision on link-format says "descriptions come from
  whichever is already available in the registry." `renderDoc`
  satisfies that requirement but it also runs a Shiki markdown
  render — ~hundreds of ms per route for 33 routes — which is
  wasted work when we only need the YAML `description` field.
  Adding `getDocMeta` as a sibling accessor keeps the parsing
  concern inside docsRegistry (single-responsibility for
  filesystem reads and frontmatter parsing) while exposing a
  cheap read for llmsTxt's use case. It is declared as a
  prerequisite and shipped in step 1 of the plan, ahead of the
  llmsTxt steps that consume it. An alternative — having llmsTxt
  call `renderDoc` and discard the HTML — would double the
  build's Shiki work and violate separation of concerns (llmsTxt
  does not need any markdown-to-HTML output).

- **Section labels come from `SECTION_INDEX_META`, not hardcoded
  strings.** `DOCS_CATEGORIES[i].label` uses `"docs"` for the
  methodology section (because it is the marketing/nav label), which
  is wrong for the H2 heading of the methodology link list. The
  llms.txt H2 headings must match the site's docs-area section
  headings exactly (the intent's strategy decision #5: four
  sections "in the canonical DOCS_CATEGORIES order — Methodology,
  Commands, Agents, Skills"). `SECTION_INDEX_META[section].label`
  already carries `"Methodology"`, `"Commands"`, `"Agents"`,
  `"Skills"` — exactly the strings the spec's Good examples show.
  Reading from `SECTION_INDEX_META` single-sources both surfaces
  and makes future label changes land in both places at once.

- **URL composition is `origin + route.urlPath`, not a format
  string in llmsTxt.** `docsRegistry` already produces
  `urlPath: "/docs/<section>/<slug>"` — the exact shape the spec
  requires. Prepending the literal origin from config is the
  minimum transformation; anything more (reconstructing the URL
  from section + slug, using a URL template) would re-introduce a
  place where the llms.txt URL shape could drift from the deployed
  site's actual routes. The `.aide` spec's bad examples call out
  this exact failure mode (URLs that look valid but 404).

- **Module-local types file (`src/service/llmsTxt/types.ts`), not
  `src/types/llmsTxt.ts`.** The playbook centralizes types in
  `src/types/` when they are shared across modules (e.g.
  `src/types/docs.ts` is read by docsRegistry, DocsSidebar, page
  components, and now llmsTxt). The three llmsTxt shapes
  (`LlmsTxtConfig`, `LinkEntry`, `RouteGroup`) are purely internal
  to this module — no other code imports them. Keeping them local
  avoids polluting the global types surface and honors the
  "keep shared code as close to its consumers as possible"
  escalation rule from the folder-structure note. If a future
  module (a sitemap generator, say) needs `LinkEntry`, the type
  lifts to `src/types/` at that point — not preemptively.

- **`verifyOutput` gates on shape + drift + forbidden substrings,
  not on exact-string equality.** Tempting to snapshot the entire
  file and fail on any diff, but that approach fails immediately
  when any docs description or title legitimately changes. The
  verifier checks structural invariants (H1 present, blockquote
  present, four H2s in correct order, every link shape-valid) and
  the four forbidden-substring classes the spec calls out
  (`AIDEY`, ` AID `, `/llms-full.txt`, `.md` URLs). This matches
  the pattern `src/service/socialShare/renderOgImage/verifyOutput/`
  established — structural gates at build time, not snapshot
  equality.

- **One H2 per category, in the four-category order, even if a
  category is empty.** The spec Good examples show four H2s
  (Methodology, Commands, Agents, Skills) and the frontmatter
  calls out "conflating the four categories into one section"
  as a failure. If docsRegistry one day reports zero skills
  routes, the verifier throws (empty section) — which is the
  correct behavior: either skills are missing from the package
  (a real bug the build should catch) or the registry broke
  (also a real bug the build should catch). Silently emitting
  three H2s would hide both.

- **The composer is split into one-responsibility helpers
  (renderHeading, renderBlockquote, renderPreamble,
  renderSection, renderLink) inside a `composeDocument/`
  orchestrator folder.** Five helpers for five distinct
  line-shapes is the right granularity — each is
  independently testable, each has a single JSDoc-able
  responsibility, and the orchestrator reads top-to-bottom as
  the exact llms.txt document order (heading → blockquote →
  preamble → sections). Inlining everything in a single
  `composeDocument/index.ts` would produce a ~80-line function
  that reviews as a wall of string concatenations; aggressive
  modularization per the progressive-disclosure convention is
  the playbook default and there is no reason to deviate.

- **No `design/` subfolder (unlike `socialShare`).** The
  socialShare precedent keeps an in-repo HTML design source
  because the rendered artifact is a binary image that must be
  byte-faithful to the HTML. llms.txt has no visual artifact,
  no fonts, no binary output — the source of truth IS the text
  the composer assembles at render time. There is nothing to
  check in.

- **No snapshot test on the full rendered llms.txt.** Snapshot
  tests for this artifact would break on every docs edit
  (legitimate or otherwise) and train the implementor to
  blanket-`--update-snapshots` when they should be reading the
  diff. The structural verifier in step 7 catches all the
  failure modes the spec lists; the unit tests in step 10
  cover the pure logic. A snapshot would add cost without
  catching anything the verifier misses.

- **Playbook notes referenced in Read lists:**
  `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions` (naming, JSDoc,
  helper placement, progressive disclosure, early returns,
  code hygiene), `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`
  (orchestrator/helper pattern, cascading domain structure,
  horizontal isolation, aggressive modularization),
  `coding-playbook/services/service-layer` (services return
  plain data, never framework types; no I/O in pure helpers),
  `coding-playbook/workflow/testing` (Vitest co-location,
  factory functions, `vi.mock` at module level, parameterized
  tests), `coding-playbook/workflow/type-system` (literal
  types for drift guards, DTO discipline).
